g.desc: The Command pattern compliments the Open Closed Principle. A ...

g.text: The Command pattern compliments the Open Closed Principle. A new Command can be introduced, referencing the Receiver, without changing the Receiver. In contrast, if the Receiver follows the Command interface then the Receiver can offer only one of its functionalities via this interface. Exposure of multiple functionalities would require a behavior switch of the Receiver and thus most likely change. Via the Command pattern we can introduce another Command and reference a different function of the same Receiver. The system can be extended without change.

g.title: Folded Corner.216
g.desc: As expressed in point (1), the Command implementation is the ...

g.text: As expressed in point (1), the Command implementation is the connection between Invoker and Receiver. This connection enables more possibilities then ‘just’ parameterizing Invoker requests. Command objects can be queued and scheduled for execution at a later moment in time. E.g. a Thread Pool that needs to queue certain requests until a Thread becomes available to execute it.

g.text: The Command Pattern compliments the Open Closed Principle. However, the flexibility that is gained comes with a cost. An additional form of indirection is added between Invoker and Receiver, namely the Command object. This indirection has negative impact on debuggability and navigate-ability of the code.

g.title: Folded Corner.235
g.desc: The Command pattern decouples Invoker from Receiver by introd...

g.text: The Command pattern decouples Invoker from Receiver by introducing a Command interface and a Command implementation. The Command interface is completely independent from the Receiver interface. This provides Invoker reusability. The same invoker can ‘act’ on series of different receivers. The Command interface is generic and might not ‘satisfy’ the receiver. The Receiver requires certain information that is passed via arguments. This is where the Command implementation comes in. The Command implementation manages dependencies required to provide the necessary information to the Receiver. Alternatively, the Receiver can also implement this generic Command interface. This means the Command implementation is not required anymore. However, this brings implementation ‘difficulties’ in case we need to connect multiple receiver functions to different Invokers.

g.title: Folded Corner.244

g.text: As expressed in point (2), the Command implementation can be applicable in multiple use-cases. One of them is to support ‘undoable’ operations. Command objects can be stored in a ‘history’ list. This list enables the possibility to traverse backwards and forwards to redo and undo a Command. (An example on how to implement undo/redo can be found on this website: https://matt.berther.io/2004/09/16/using-the-command-pattern-for-undo-functionality/)

g.title: Folded Corner.251
g.desc: The Command Pattern both compliments and violates the Single ...

g.text: The Command Pattern both compliments and violates the Single Responsibility Principle. The Command pattern introduces an additional Command Class instead of ‘binding’ the Invoker and the Receiver directly via an interface. This additional Command class can make logic more scattered, because the responsibility could also be fulfilled by the Receiver directly. The code becomes harder to comprehend.

g.title: Folded Corner.254
g.desc: The Command Pattern compliments Single Responsibility. The Re...

g.text: The Command Pattern compliments Single Responsibility. The Receiver and Invoker are loosely coupled from each other via the Command interface and implementation. This enables that Invoker and Receiver can ‘evolve’ independently. The Command implementation has one responsibility namely to handle a request (execute, undo/redo and to load and store). The Command object uses the required dependencies to parametrize the Receiver. Excluding this command logic from the Receiver makes the Receiver easier testable. Easier testable, because the problem window of our Receiver becomes smaller. Excluding this logic from the Invoker, makes the Invoker more reusable for other Receivers.

g.text: The Command pattern can be used to log executed commands to disk. A log file is generated based on the Commands that are performed. Recovering from a crash involves reading the log file and re-executing the commands.

g.title: Folded Corner.269
g.desc: The Command Pattern compliments the Interface Segregation Pri...

g.text: The Command Pattern compliments the Interface Segregation Principle. The Invoker is dependent on a ‘focused’ Command interface. This overcomes the dependency on a possible ‘extensive’ interface of the Receiver. The dependency on a ‘focused’ Command interface enhances testability, reusability and reduces re-compilation of the Invoker. Testability, because the mock effort will be lower and interface changes in unused functionality will not reflect on the Receiver mock used by the Invoker. Reusability, because Invoker doesn’t reference an ‘extensive’ Receiver interface directly, making the Invoker better reusable for other Receivers. Less re-compilation, because a change in the Receiver interface will not reflect on the Invoker.
